post_text:
Congratulations to WHS Senior Hunter LeClair, who was recently announced as a 2020-21 National Merit Semifinalist!

Out of 1.5 million test takers, only 16,000 received this distinguished academic award. Hunter will now advance to the Finalist round. Finalists will be selected by a thorough review of transcripts, test scores, a detailed application, and an essay, and they will be recognized in February.

We are proud of you, Hunter!

post_text:
A message from Head Football Coach, Scott Syrjala:

For anyone interested in playing HIGH SCHOOL football this year, we begin our season on Monday, August 10th. Please report to the practice field behind the school and see Coach Syrjala or Coach Gray. We will be following all mandated rules set forth by the MHSAA in regards to COVID-19. You will need cleats and a face mask. A "gator" mask is recommended. They can be purchased locally at Wilderness Sports for $6. You will also need to bring your own water bottle, marked with your name on it. If you do not have a physical after April 2019 - you must obtain one before you can practice. Last year's physical WILL WORK for this year, according to the MHSAA. If you have any questions, please contact Coach Syrjala at 361-1858.

For those researching educational options for their students this fall, our Patriot Online Academy (POA) has been in existence for over ten years and is free for students. Our POA utilizes the latest online educational platforms and programming. Parents and guardians are welcome to contact our Aspen Ridge School Office (which serves our Kindergarten through 8th Grade students) at 485-3175 or our Westwood High School Office (serving our 9th-12th Grade students) at 485-1023. Both offices are open weekdays from 7am until 3pm. You can also contact POA Director Kurt Corcoran at: corcorank@nice.k12.mi.us
We are here to help.
Please utilize the contact information above so that we can correspond with you directly. Our apologies, our Facebook page is not regularly monitored to cover questions and answers.

We are on for tonight's 2020 Graduation Celebration. It looks like we'll have a bit of a storm starting around 4:45pm and ending right around 6pm. Our celebration will begin at 7pm. Our ceremony is limited to invited guests only due to social distancing restrictions. We will have a live streaming Facebook broadcast. ESPN UP will broadcast on 93.3 FM, 970 AM, espnup.com, and the ESPN UP app.
Invited guests are reminded to bring their own lawn chairs if they can; they'll be more comfortable than our loaner folding chairs.
Entry for guests begins at 6pm.
We asked everyone to keep in mind social distancing guidelines when it comes to members outside one's own family.
Congratulations to our WHS Class of 2020! Go Patriots!

Westwood’s Cybersecurity teams have excelled in two competitions over the past months.

On Tuesday, June 16, the Michigan CyberPatriot organization held a virtual awards session for CyberPatriot XII, where Westwood’s team consisting of Aili Harmon, Trent Holmgren, Makenzie Rajala, Chloe Grochowski, Luke Mariuzza and Luke Vidlund was awarded the 3rd place award in the Silver Tier in Michigan, receiving a trophy in recognition of that award.

The second competition involved the Westwood Girls Go CyberStart team of Makenzie Rajala, Aili Harmon, Meg Harmon and Avery Mariuzza, which qualified for the National Championships and competed as a team from their individual homes on May 20-21, placing 125th in the nation.

Congratulations to the students from both teams for their success in these competitions!

Unfortunately this game has been canceled but we want to send a huge congratulations to Senior Erik Anderson for being selected to the State of Michigan’s East-West Shrine All-Star game.

Very few players from the Upper Peninsula get to play in this game. This year, Erik was the only player in the entire U.P. to be selected. Way to go, Erik! Hard work does pay!

Congratulations to our senior wrestler Rocco Carlson on achieving Individual Academic All-State from the Michigan Wrestling Association.

Rocco was 1 of only 4 wrestlers from the U.P. to earn this honor.

Rocco will be attending Michigan Technological University in the fall.

Also, congratulations to our Westwood Wrestling team for earning Team Academic All-State for the 4th year in a row!

Well done wrestlers and thank you to our coaches, teachers, staff and administration.

Photos courtesy: Daryl Jarvinen and Jennifer Sevegney

Attention Current 8th Graders:

The staff members at Westwood High School were so bummed that we couldn't have an orientation for you, so we decided to bring the orientation to YOU!

In the next day or so, you will receive a letter in the mail from Mr. Fossitt (your new principal!), a curriculum guide, and a course registration form. After viewing the virtual orientation below, please complete the course registration and mail it back to Mrs. Halamka by May 1st. You can also just send her an email with your course requests.

If you have any questions at all, please contact Mrs. Halamka or Mr. Fossitt by phone or email. We can't wait to see you in the fall!

All the best,
Your Westwood High School Teachers and Staff

Hello, NICE Families and Friends. Nothing like a fresh foot of April snow to lighten our moods, eh? I'm a winter lover, but I am ready for spring and summer to brighten up our lovely U.P.
I have a few meetings today, including one with Michigan Senate Majority Leader Mike Shirkey who's out of the 16th Senate District downstate. I'll report back if any new information comes to light about anything important. I think we have all the most up-to-date information that's available as it pertains to schools.
Otherwise, it's a regular Monday in this temporary new-normal. We'll continue to manage our hiatus in April, May, and the first week in June. We'll break for summer and continue to work on an optional Summer School Refresher Program for parts of August. We'll also continue to gear up for the new school year.
Until then, continue to take care of yourselves, your families, and each other. We will get through this. I'll be on the virtual run today, so I won't be able to weigh in again on this post. I will write again soon.
All my best,
Bryan DeAugustine
Superintendent

post_text:
Congratulations to Anastasia Bjork, WHS alum from the Class of 2016, for her accomplishments at Central Michigan University.

Join us in wishing her continued success as she heads to Finland in the fall to continue her studies.

#patriotpride
shared_text:
Central Michigan University Honors Program
April 9 at 6:29 PM ·

Anastasia Bjork, an Honors senior, has been selected to receive a prestigious Fulbright Study Grant to Tampere University in Finland. Anastasia will begin a master's degree in Public Choice in fall 2020, a program which incorporates the use of economics to address societal problems, such as health care. The Fulbright grant provides a monthly stipend, a full tuition scholarship, and a travel award. Anastasia will also learn about Finnish culture and share American culture with her host community to help achieve the Fulbright goal of building mutual understanding between peoples of the U.S. and other countries.

Congratulations Anastasia!

The CMU National Scholarship Program is now accepting pre-applications for the 2021-2022 competition, deadline April 10. For more information about how you can apply, contact Dr. Maureen Harke at harke1ma@cmich.edu or visit the CMU National Scholarship Program webpage.

post_text:
Good morning. As I imagine you may have heard by now, our State is closing our schools for the remainder of this school year. We are going to be okay. Our seniors will still be graduating, our students will still be moving to their next grade level. We will back-fill these missing learning days with a combination of online learning activities that will begin next week as planned, lessons broadcast over public television that we are working on with our regional education partners, and possibly some optional face-to-face summer school days in August. (The face-to-face summer school days will be 100% voluntary and optional if we are able to make them happen.)
For now, please continue to rest and relax. We've got this and will navigate these waters together. My apologies, but I will not be able to respond to comments on this thread. I will be in touch as we continue to digest this new set of directions from our State.
All my best,
Bryan DeAugustine
Superintendent

Good afternoon. I've had a host of meetings this morning with agencies across the State of Michigan. For better or worse, there are really no updates to report regarding schools. For now, we are still on the State-ordered hiatus through April 13.
We will continue to hold fast and prepare for our face-to-face operations to resume after our hiatus ends. I know it's easier to type than to do, but I hope everyone tries their best to rest and relax during these unusual times. Taking care of yourselves and your families is the best thing any of us can do right now.
Until we are back up and running, I will be in touch with updates and will reach out as soon as any new information is available. We will make it through this.
All my best,
Bryan DeAugustine
Superintendent

Hello. We had a conference call with the Michigan Department of Education this morning. They reiterated their directive to us to simply hold fast and treat the next three weeks as if we are on a really long Spring Break. They have directed us to cease all student activities including coursework or enrichment activities until the State ordered three-week school hiatus has concluded. The NICE Community School District would like to invite members of the community to participate in the selection of two teachers who exemplify teaching excellence and who have had a significant and positive impact on students.

One Elementary Teacher and one Secondary Teacher will be honored at the annual Excellence in Education Day in May along with top the academic performing students.

Nomination forms are now being accepted for the 2019-2020 school year. These forms are available to all community members at each school office or printable here. Nominations will not be accepted via Facebook. Please submit a hard copy nomination form for it to be considered. Thank you.

Have a great Friday and a great weekend.
All my best,
Bryan DeAugustine

post_text:
The following Westwood High School students were selected for and participated in the 2020 WSMA Menominee River Conference Honors Band on January 17th and 18th at Niagara High School in Niagara, WI.

The Menominee River Conference Honors Band is comprised of more than 80 students selected from many Upper Peninsula and Northeast Wisconsin schools. Students are nominated by their member school and selected by a committee of conference directors. These students spent two long days rehearsing and improving their musicianship with award-winning and internationally acclaimed band composer and music educator Mr. William Owens from Fort Worth Texas (pictured below with our WHS students).

Katelyn Anttila, Flute
Brianna Stephens, Flute
Kaylee LaMere, Clarinet
Allison Korpi, Alto Sax
Heidi Hinkens, Tenor Sax
Jackson Vidlund, Trumpet
Alex Adriano, Trumpet
Jacob Mattson, Horn
Landon Ouellette, Trombone
Valentino Anderson, Tuba
Micah Milano, Percussion
Noah Penrose, Percussion

We congratulate these students for a terrific achievement!

post_text: We would like to send a big shout out and hearty congratulations to Mr. David Boase. Mr. Boase's final day of work will be this Friday as our first semester draws to a close. He has been our high school principal for the past twenty years and is retiring to pursue some opportunities in private industry. (Mr. Boase worked downstate for several years prior to returning home to the U.P.) We are happy that we'll still see him at our extracurricular events as his two sons complete their education here at Westwood High School. Congratulations, Mr. Boase! Thank you for being such a great part of our school family.

We would like to thank our Schools of Choice students and their families for choosing us as their school family. Over 20% of our student population comes from our Schools of Choice students; we hover around 260 SOC students each year. Combined with our students who live within our district boundaries, we have an excellent group of kids and young adults here at NICE Community Schools. We are truly proud of our young people and we are excited as our first semester draws to a close and the start of our second semester is about to begin.

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians,

I’m writing to drop you a quick note regarding our parking lots and access road. Please remember to drive slowly and cautiously when on our campus. The access road is not a street. The speed limit is 15 mph when the road is clear. When students are present, especially in the mornings and afternoons, I ask that you drive even slower.

I know life is hectic. Nothing, however, is worth risking a collision with another vehicle or a pedestrian. Please remember to slow down, take your time, and look out for our kids and each other. A school’s greatest strength is a commitment to the school family taking care of one another in ways big and small. Please help out by driving carefully in our parking lots and on our access road.

Thank you and welcome back.

All my best,
Bryan DeAugustine
Superintendent

Congratulations, ladies!

Pictured from left to right are Westwood High School students and local winners Sarina Maki, 1st place, Chloe Grochowski, 3rd place, Irv Krellwitz, Post Commander, and Meg Harmon, 2nd place. Sarina went on to place 4th at the district level.

Congratulations, ladies!

post_text: We'd like to send out a big congratulations for another excellent winter concert season! Following a long tradition, today's elementary concerts were a hit! In addition, both of our recent WHS and ARMS Winter Concerts were also smashing successes and there is excited anticipation for our choral concerts next Tuesday at 1pm and 7pm. Our Music Department is truly special. Our directors are Laura Woolard, Betsy Grugin, Gordon Erickson, and Tony Beacco. We'd also like to thank our 2019 Student Parking Crew. They also upheld a fine tradition in making the most of our very snowy parking lots. Thank you, students! Happy Holidays!

The Westwood High School & Aspen Ridge 8th grade winter band concert is tonight at 7:00 p.m. in the Patriot Performing Arts Theatre. The Aspen Ridge 6th and 7th grade winter band concert will be tomorrow at 7:00 p.m. in the Aspen Ridge gymnasium. A suggested donation of $3.00 for individuals or $10.00 per family is recommended for admission for these two concerts.

The Aspen Ridge Elementary Christmas Programs will take place on Thursday, December 12, in the Westwood High School gymnasium. Pre-K through 2nd grade students will perform in “A Taste of Christmas” at 10:00 a.m., while students in grades 3-5 will perform “A World of Christmas” beginning at 1:00 p.m. Doors open one hour before the start time and admission is free for these two concerts.

I want to wish everyone a Happy Thanksgiving before everyone scatters for the actual holiday itself. I am thankful to be part of such a great school community. I want to thank our students, parents, guardians, faculty and staff for an excellent start to the school year. As fall fades in our rear-view mirror, I'm excited for the start of our winter activities and all that lies ahead. Please have a fantastic holiday season.

Bryan DeAugustine
Superintendent
(Photo courtesy of Down Wind Sports, taken at Bridal Veil Falls in Munising, MI on Sunday, November 17, before the most recent warm up.)

Congratulations to the Aspen Ridge Middle School Robotic Strong ARMS teams who competed over the weekend in Kingsford. Both teams performed very well and competed in the semi-final Alliance Matches.

Strong ARMS Blue was honored with 2nd place in the Connect Award. Strong ARMS Red was honored with 1st place in the Collins Aerospace Innovate Award, 3rd place in the Connect Award, and 3rd place in the Inspire Award. Robotic Strong ARMS Red will be competing in the state finals December 13-14.

Way to go Robotic Strong ARMS!

NICE Community Schools would like to thank Mrs. Claire Brewer for a generous donation to the Westwood High School Auto Repair Class.

The scholarship money will be awarded to an Auto Repair student at the culmination of the 2019-2020 school year.

Mrs. Brewer is the mother of the late Steven and Bill Brewer (WHS Class of 1981 and Class of 1987) and grandmother to recent Westwood alumni Ciara, Seth, Austin, and Nathan Brewer.

Thank you to the Brewer family for the support!

Reminder to all Seniors and their Parents/Guardians:

There is a Financial Aid meeting and workshop tonight at 6:30 p.m. at Negaunee High School. Parents/guardians and students should both attend.

Financial Aid faculty from NMU will be there to first do a presentation on the FAFSA and components of student aid. NHS will then open their computer labs for families who would like to fill out the FAFSA on site with assistance from the Financial Aid professionals.

If you are planning on attending the workshop, please bring the following information: your driver's license, social security number (student and parent), federal income tax returns (from 2018 for both student and parent), and any records of un-taxed income.

If you have any questions, please call Mrs. Halamka in the Guidance Office at (906) 485-1023.

Excellent breaking news to report in the world of cybersecurity. For the second year in a row, we have a cybersecurity team in the Top 10 in the State of Michigan. Our Westwood Patriots 1 Cybersecurity Team has earned a spot in the State Finals later this fall where the Top 10 teams will face-off for the State Title. Over 600 students across the state competed in this year's Governor's Cyber Challenge. We will have more information to follow. Go Patriots!
Our Patriots 1 Cybersecurity Team Members are Aili Harmon, Trent Holmgren, and Makenzie Rajala.
Our Cybersecurity Instructors are Ronalyn Arseneau and Sabina Villar.

post_text: Amy Anderson from the American Cancer Society stopped by today to thank us for participating in last year's Real Yoopers Wear Pink fundraising and awareness campaign. Although Superintendent DeAugustine isn't a contestant this year, Ms. Anderson wants us to keep our eyes out for this year's Real Yoopers wearing pink during the month of October so that we can help support cancer awareness and research. Here's to eradicating all forms of cancer once and for all!
